social_posts.post_text:
Thank you all from the bottom of my heart for following along and for everyone who purchased art this year! This year marks 8 years of pursuing art full time. I’m able to do it because of all of you. I hope everyone is enjoying new art and ornaments. I am excited for the new series I have planned in the new year! For now, I’m going to go post up on the beach and enjoy some time off! Sending love to you all! Happy Holidays!! ❤️

If you need me reach me on email, I’ll be checking that regularly: Katiejacobsonart@gmail.com

Happy new year!! Hope everyone has had a great holiday break. We celebrated in Hawaii, soaking up a lot of sunshine and nature. It was a nice way to refresh after a very busy fall. It’s been lovely having time off and I look forward to getting into the studio tomorrow! Taking time off has my inspiration booming. I have been journaling on my goals for this year and having visions of new paintings I can’t wait to create. I am ecstatic to paint and to get these new ideas flowing! I will also be opening up my commission for window tomorrow. I’ll share more on this tomorrow!

I’m releasing new floral drawings January 17th at 8pm EST, 3pm Hawaii time. Drawing with charcoal is something I’ve always loved. This year I have a goal to do more of it. Gesture drawing is like a dance between your eyes, brain, and hand. It’s about letting loose and capturing the energy of what is in front of you. 
Excited to share more on this new series leading up to the release!

These two framed graphite drawings will be available at 8pm est (3pm Hawaii) I found these beautiful vintage frames I absolutely love! They feel special and unique. I have 6 of them total but wanted to use two for these drawings. I had custom double mats made to freshen them up and give them contrast. They will be sold separately, even though I love them as a pair. These pieces are graceful and feminine to being some subtle love to your walls!

Valentine’s Day commissions options! I am only taking a few! First to book get the spots! Email Katiejacobsonart@gmail.com to book. 
(Please don’t DM to book, I’m not sure if I get all my messages so I might miss yours)

Been having some fun in our backyard this weekend! For months I’ve had an idea of a pillows I wanted. I ordered all the silk painting material and have been playing around! I have started with silk chiffon scarfs to get the hang of it, then I’m moving onto the thick soft silk. Once I have those painted I’ll be going to get them upholstered into pillows. Hand painted silk pillows here we go⭐️

My husband gave me lilies one day and I had them on a vase sitting on our kitchen table. The way to light comes in during the afternoon always catches my eye. I had to paint this moment to capture the transience that I found so beautiful. Appreciating beauty in the mundane makes everyday brighter. 🌞

It’s coming up on one year since we moved to Hawaii. It’s wild how fast it’s flown while also how long ago last winter feels. Life feels new in so many ways. Moving so far from home, there’s those moments where you want to cling to what you are comfortable with… that’s the challenge in big change. But over and over again learn that growth happens when you embrace that you are expanding and everything is evolving. I’m looking forward to seeing how the inspiration continues to evolve in art and in myself. Hawaii is so good for the soul 🌞
Pictured here is some of my paintings of Hawaii from 2022. I’m looking forward to showing art work here for the first time next month! I’m working on a new Hawaii inspired collection. I’ll be sharing more on this soon.

Thank you for following along! ❤️

From my notes: “I hope for the viewer to be inspired to stop and observe the patterns light creates in this painting and in their everyday life. The abstraction of colors that light creates on a reflective surface is a meditation simply by being in an observation mode. The second dimension to this presence is appreciating the transience of the experience. The sun and objects shift, the weather changes which affects every color and the lighting entirely. Anything and everything apart of this moment will grow, die, or move. I personally find an overwhelming gratitude for this ethereal existence, that even small moments like this hold. There is so much beauty and power in small moments.”

This collection will be available March 10th at 10am EST. If you have any questions email Katiejacobsonart@gmail.com

There are a million people painting flowers out there. We all have unique experiences with them and our own process. It’s never about being the best, it’s just about being you. Artist paint what inspires them, period. For years I was scared to paint flowers because so many other artists painted them. Something I heard at one point that has stuck with me is “fear is resistance”. Resisting to express something you love, is like closing off apart of who you are. 

  I am a flower hoarder. I collect all kinds of orchids. I love taking clippings from our yard and putting them in bud vases in thoughtful places around the house. My husband always greets me at the airport with flowers. When I have a vase of flowers they will be in the most prominent place in the house and might be moving room to room with me. I even take the dying flowers from the flower shop. They are one of my very favorite things. 

  Surrounding myself with its these beautiful living things makes everything I am experiencing more beautiful. I think most of us relate. 

The truth is that flowers make such an impact. I remember all the flowers I had during covid lockdown and how much joy they brought. I remember the lilies my parents gave me after my high school dance recital. There are countless visual memories of flowers I have experienced. 

Painting flowers makes them last forever.

One of those moments I wish flowers lasted forever🥀

Two of my favorite places to paint in Highlands: a secret lily pond and the Chattooga River. 

A funny memory… One time when I was out painting  plein air at this lily pond, dark skies rolled in fast. Lighting crashing, and thunder booming. I was hustling to get my paints and paintings to my car… literally running. I ran straight into a short rhododendron stump and broke two toes. My mom took me to the doctor to get X-rays and we laughed (and I cried). Couldn’t believe that happened. The dangers of painting 😂 

Both these locations bring me so much peace while I sit out there painting. I’ve been working on these new paintings from all my photos and videos. Working on this collection has been bringing me that peace. I enter a dream state thinking about the mountain air and smells. 

I am so excited about this show and getting to spend more time in Highlands this August 🤍

I’ve felt the ebb and flow of challenges and gratitude recently. Some days just feel normal and routine. There have also been emotions with challenges that have been coming up. Then there are those moments where awe and gratitude really settles in. Like the beautiful moment you see something you see all the time with fresh eyes. Or when the right song comes on the while driving in a beautiful scene. Even things like seeing a movie or reading a book gives you a fresh perspective.

Some days have been stressful focusing on worries and feeling depleted. Then there are days where my eyes feel brighter and more absorbent. 

Whether big or small, we are in constant ebb and flow. Challenges will come but at the same time new beauty and awareness will arise. That perfect mix helps us stay in evolution to grow. 
Challenges can feel difficult in the moment, but working through them helps us grow. If everything always was easy, we wouldn’t grow into where and who we want to be. 

Pictured here are recent moments that brought big gratitude. These are highlights. The thing you don’t see is my worries about the economy and it’s affect on art sales, how the algorithm has been hurting small business, or me crying over a shipping mishap that happened. Whether small or big… real life is here and happens. We learn how to pivot and grow. Times like these make us get creative and adjust. These gratitudes and highlights are what keep me going. Gratitude inspires and makes me feel love which lifts me over and over again. Because it all ebbs and flows. 🙏

New landscape series is in progress and will be available next month. This collection embodies the peace that being in solitude in wide open landscapes brings. I always feel a great sense of peace looking out in the endless ocean, gazing at the vast space in the mountains out west, or sitting on a dock at the lake. Those moments are grounding and essential for my inner peace. There is a humbling reminder to how small our thoughts are compared to the rolling beauty all around us. I want this collection to breathe that into the spaces where they hang. 
The process has been intentional and required me to step back, think, and dream a lot. There is a softness and transparency I’m working to achieve in these. 
I’ll announce a date and time soon💌

I’m starting a painting a day back tomorrow, November 1st. I’ll be doing this for November and December. Everyday I’ll do a painting and share a time lapse. The painting will be available on my website everyday after it’s complete. 
I’ve decided to do this instead of doing any more releases this year. I love doing the daily painting so much because it allows me to bounce around subject wise and it makes me very present with what inspires me on a daily basis. It helps keeps accountable to show up to the easel everyday. It’s so fun waking up and asking myself… what do I feel like painting today? 
I’m always open for something you want to see me paint too! Leave a comment if you have any suggestions!

Feels good to be back to a painting a day! It takes a pressure off that’s hard to explain. I am able to embrace my ADD and do whatever my Inspiration bounces from that day. There’s such a freedom to it. Not to mention a great practice for skill and just making me show up to the easel. 
Today’s painting is ‘Start the Day’. Three things that a staple for me every single morning… lemons, eggs, and avocado. Morning routines make me feel good. In our daily routines it’s easy to miss the beauty in everything around you. It’s so cool how sitting with this still life how vibrant colors become when I step into really observing it. It’s a great reminder to stop and really appreciate your surroundings. Study the life around you and you’ll step into a greater gratitude.

A painting a day 11/16 — painted from life 
My sister in law working on her laptop. 

Something I think about a lot is how much I love paint to talk. Which is one of the main reasons why oil paint is my absolute favorite medium. It’s like butter. It can be pushed and pulled and layered. With this figure study I really focused on the paint and letting it talk through the application. 
Figure painting (and drawing) is something I miss often from college. We worked from live models a majority of the time. Studying color from life is a whole different color experience than painting from photo. And painting the figure is such a great practice. It felt so good to do it again! 

The painting a day is something my professor told me about in college. Coming back to this practice over and over again has been so good for me to to expand creativity, to re-align to purpose in painting, and most of all put fire under curiosity. I’m forever a student of painting, and that makes me feel excited. On day 16 of the painting a day and it has made me excited about painting all over again.
Back on the painting a day! Today painting ranunculus from life. Available, link in bio!🌞

Nine years ago I packed up my car and moved to Denver. Along with moving across the country, it was also the moment I took a leap of faith to pursue art full time. There has been ALOT of learning curves and growth in the last nine ears. Moments of feeling like I should give up. Balanced with moments of celebration. But anytime I’ve reached that point of question, reevaluation and reassurance happen to remind me why I’m doing this. I still am figuring it out, because there is constant room for growth and things are always changing. Painting is the most natural thing I’ve felt since I was a child. It’s my happy place, my therapy, my gratitude, and most of all it’s practice that I really love. My idea of where it all will go is wide open. All I know is I’m devoted to showing up everyday and to having fun with that. 
This community is the reason why I’m here. I’m beyond thankful for you all, supporting my art for all these years. From Denver, to Nashville, to Taos NM, back to Columbus GA many times, and now Hawaii… y’all have been there following along through this platform. Thank you from the bottom of my heart for being here ❤️
